segments.text: Did family, background, ancestry, race, national origin have anything to do with?
Outside of work ethic, no.
No, because we had every type.
We had Bohunks, Polacks, no names.
We had wealthy.
We had poor.
It didn't make any difference what your dad did.
It didn't make any difference where they had gone to school, where they lived.
A&M, you know, friends at Texas, friends at SMU, TCU, Rice, Baylor, family status was always important to somebody somewhere along the way, but not at A&M.
A&M was, everybody's the same because we're all in this thing together.
And if you choose to run against the wind, pack your bags.
If you're a tattletale or if you're a whiner,

you weren't welcome in the outfit they welcomed everybody until they turned until somebody turns on the outfit you don't squeal on your fish buddies you stand together and I don't know I think that's you want to talk about Aggie spirit it is about that bonding together under and you get the same thing in troops in combat and things like that but they're they're shipped out and gone this was
One year of being a freshman, but also four years of living together in the Corps of Cadets.
And I hate to say it, there's no way that these kids that live in apartments that ride, take their automobile in, get that class and leave, they're not part of the A&M experience, unfortunately.
Right.
Now, I don't need to ask you the next question.
What did you learn at A&M that's been important in your life?
You just said that.
If you were a consultant to the A&M leadership today,
What advice would you give them about making A&M's future as bright as possible?

I would continue to do everything I could to encourage continuation and membership in the Corps of Cadets and to do everything I could from ever making any organization an elitist organization that could have money tied to it of any kind.
I don't even know about Caldwell House, except it's very expensive to live there.
But A&M has always been a place for a poor kid from the country to go to school.
Now, I'm fine to make money, but it's OK to go to college without wearing polo shirts and dressing to the nines and driving a BMW.
I would continue Bonfire as it was.
Safety measures can be implemented.
Supervision is there and you can get outside people, A&M or not A&M, you can get outside expertise to help from safety, engineering safety, structure.
It can be done.
It's too valuable a tradition to lose.
These are the things that I would like to see continue.
Remember the strengths that this school was born on and why it was a school for the common man.
It doesn't mean lower your standards, keep your standards high, but require something more.
Next to the last question.

If you could make a major gift to Texas A&M, let's make believe that somebody hands you a check for a million dollars and there's one restriction on it, it must be passed on to A&M, but you can decide what would be done with it.
What would you have A&M do with a major gift if you could make one?
I would give it to the Corps of Cadets and I would not put it into programs so much as I would put it into

probably a mixture of continued leadership training, perhaps better housing, perhaps Corps scholarships to recruit the best and the brightest to make it worthwhile for people on the outside to see, hey, this could be a good deal.
And then encourage anything we could to make the Corps, which is so central to the experience at A&M, I would give every penny of it to the Corps of Cadets.
One of the things that the Corps is not doing these days, Corps leadership, as far as I'm aware, they are not going out to recruit bright juniors.
They're waiting until March and April of their senior year.
Way too late.
Well, he decided long ago where he was going to go to college.
And the brighter they are, the earlier the hustle.

i i really think that they need to do they need to target juniors yes and on spend the night with the corps they need to be very careful and i would encourage the leadership that whatever outside of your cadets whatever military personnel you have i would make dead level sure that they are hand-picked for the job to deal with these high school students who are in the primordia when they're in those formative
years of thinking about where they're going to go to school, that sophomore, that junior.
Let's get that military officer that can be conversant and answer the questions that the parents have and the kid has.
And those are hard to find in today's military.
And if not military, maybe some advisors, some people that have been there.
But yeah, those would be my concerns.
Last question.
Last question.
What feelings do you hold for Texas A&M in your heart today?
Warm and fuzzy.
It's an emotional experience that comes and goes when you hear the war hymn.
I left the drill field in 1972.
I'm not one of these Aggies that
I don't have to beat every football game.
We go about once, I will go to a few more now.
Boys are starting to school, but it's more than who's paid professional athletes can move the pigskin up and down the football field.
I'm sick of it, but it's still, you know, we still like, you know, A&M football games are neat, I guess, but very...
Deep, probably the single most important driving force next to my salvation as a Christian has been my four years in the Corps of Cadets at A&M.
Did more to, for better or for worse, for me as an individual.
They made my service life easy.
That made practice life easy.
Whatever else I have done in community or veterinary medicine, whatever awards and things I've gotten are all colored by my four years at A&M.
Not Robert E. Lee High School, not Trinity Day School, but those four years at Texas A&M in the Corps of Cadets did more to mold me for better or for worse than the person I am.
So, yeah, some deep emotion, very deep emotion.
That's a good place to go.
